00:03:49.154 --> 00:03:51.070
CHRISTOPHER PATNOE: So
bringing in the concept

00:03:51.070 --> 00:03:54.010
of inclusive design,
many people ask, well,

00:03:54.010 --> 00:03:55.780
what is inclusive design?

00:03:55.780 --> 00:03:59.260
Well, to me, it means being
mindful in your choices

00:03:59.260 --> 00:04:01.780
so that you don't exclude
someone accidentally

00:04:01.780 --> 00:04:03.820
by a lack of thought.

00:04:03.820 --> 00:04:05.970
The way I got involved
here in accessibility

00:04:05.970 --> 00:04:07.800
is when I was on
Google Play Music.

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:11.140
A test engineer came up
and brought her device

00:04:11.140 --> 00:04:13.210
and a speaker, plugged them in.

00:04:13.210 --> 00:04:15.625
I heard button,
button, button, button.

00:04:15.625 --> 00:04:17.500
And I'm seeing people
smile here, because you

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:18.375
know what this means.

00:04:18.375 --> 00:04:19.852
But I didn't at the time.

00:04:19.852 --> 00:04:22.310
What this means is that the
application was not accessible.

00:04:22.310 --> 00:04:24.250
So I asked, what is this?

00:04:24.250 --> 00:04:26.824
And she said, well, this
is your application.

00:04:26.824 --> 00:04:27.990
I said, well, that's stupid.

00:04:27.990 --> 00:04:29.160
How does someone use it?

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:31.810
And she said, this
is why I'm here.

00:04:31.810 --> 00:04:33.790
And it was at that
moment that I realized

00:04:33.790 --> 00:04:36.570
that it takes zero effort
to make your experience

00:04:36.570 --> 00:04:38.800
or application not inclusive.

00:04:38.800 --> 00:04:41.300
It only takes a little
bit to make it inclusive.

00:04:41.300 --> 00:04:43.210
So that's what we're
here to talk about.

00:04:43.210 --> 00:04:46.990
And accessibility is
one of the key lenses,

00:04:46.990 --> 00:04:50.770
one of the most tangible
lenses for inclusive design.

00:04:50.770 --> 00:04:53.260
Well, why is
accessibility important?

00:04:53.260 --> 00:04:54.940
Well, one, it's the
right thing to do.

00:04:54.940 --> 00:04:57.680
And two, it's
potentially big business.

00:04:57.680 --> 00:04:59.320
There are more than
one billion people

00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:03.730
in the world who have some
form of disability, about 15%.

00:05:03.730 --> 00:05:05.390
About one in five
people in the US

00:05:05.390 --> 00:05:09.226
will have a disability at
some point in their lives.

00:05:09.226 --> 00:05:10.850
Just to give you
another sense of this,

00:05:10.850 --> 00:05:13.940
there are more than 300 million
people who are colorblind.

00:05:13.940 --> 00:05:16.120
That's more people who
are colorblind that are

00:05:16.120 --> 00:05:18.462
people of the United States--

00:05:18.462 --> 00:05:20.170
and I think that's
important to remember,

00:05:20.170 --> 00:05:22.820
is accessibility is a spectrum.

00:05:22.820 --> 00:05:25.180
It's not a binary on, off thing.

00:05:25.180 --> 00:05:26.860
Many common
ailments, you may not

00:05:26.860 --> 00:05:29.050
recognize have
[INAUDIBLE] disabilities

00:05:29.050 --> 00:05:33.210
is like nearsightedness,
arthritis, or even a bad back.

00:05:33.210 --> 00:05:37.030
And there are still lots of
nuances within these groupings

00:05:37.030 --> 00:05:38.350
of disabilities.

00:05:38.350 --> 00:05:40.960
It's more like cups
instead of buckets.

00:05:40.960 --> 00:05:43.150
Because as there are
individual people and people

00:05:43.150 --> 00:05:45.400
have different abilities,
people have different kinds

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:46.066
of disabilities.

00:05:46.066 --> 00:05:47.440
And they're very subtle.

00:05:47.440 --> 00:05:51.430
But fortunately, the things
that help these different groups

00:05:51.430 --> 00:05:54.770
bring up all the boats up
together at the same time.

00:05:54.770 --> 00:05:57.760
You also want to think about
situational or temporary

00:05:57.760 --> 00:06:03.460
impairments like a broken leg
or carrying a bag of groceries

00:06:03.460 --> 00:06:05.950
or even using your
device with bright sun.

00:06:05.950 --> 00:06:08.680
All of these things are
situational impairments.

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:12.310
And finally, different people
learn at different speeds,

00:06:12.310 --> 00:06:15.265
either by disability
or simply stress.

00:06:17.810 --> 00:06:20.810
So the core thing I want
you to come away with is

00:06:20.810 --> 00:06:22.730
don't design for yourself.

00:06:22.730 --> 00:06:24.530
Design for the broadest
possible markets.

00:06:24.530 --> 00:06:28.340
And you'll be surprised
who you're supporting.

00:06:28.340 --> 00:06:30.170
How do you do this, do you ask?

00:06:30.170 --> 00:06:31.515
Well, I'm glad you asked.

00:06:31.515 --> 00:06:32.890
One of the ways
I talk about this

00:06:32.890 --> 00:06:34.710
is a thing called the curb cut.

00:06:34.710 --> 00:06:36.980
What a curb cut is is
that part of the sidewalk

00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:39.980
that is dipped down, usually
in the corner of blocks.

00:06:39.980 --> 00:06:42.080
This is designed to allow
people with wheelchairs

00:06:42.080 --> 00:06:44.720
to be able to get up
onto the sidewalk.

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:46.910
That's really
profoundly important.

00:06:46.910 --> 00:06:49.250
But it's also really useful
for people with suitcases

00:06:49.250 --> 00:06:51.470
or bicycles or baby strollers.

00:06:51.470 --> 00:06:53.900
So the idea of a
curb cut is something

00:06:53.900 --> 00:06:56.300
that can help many
people, but it's

00:06:56.300 --> 00:06:58.730
profoundly impactful,
profoundly impactful

00:06:58.730 --> 00:07:00.620
for people with disabilities.

00:07:00.620 --> 00:07:03.350
Another example, if
you had to help address

00:07:03.350 --> 00:07:05.390
the needs of someone
who is hard of hearing,

00:07:05.390 --> 00:07:08.870
you're also helping people
who forgot their ear buds.

00:07:08.870 --> 00:07:11.730
And just so you know, this
means captions, for example.

00:07:11.730 --> 00:07:13.910
You're helping people who
forgot their ear buds.

00:07:13.910 --> 00:07:15.980
You're helping people
on a noisy train,

00:07:15.980 --> 00:07:18.430
or conversely in
a quiet room where

00:07:18.430 --> 00:07:20.930
you don't want to make
a lot of noise, or even

00:07:20.930 --> 00:07:22.730
non-native speakers.

00:07:22.730 --> 00:07:25.670
This one accommodation can help
lots of people, more people

00:07:25.670 --> 00:07:29.000
than you might realize
at the beginning.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:29.940
Another example.

00:07:29.940 --> 00:07:31.898
And here's one that's
really close to my heart,

00:07:31.898 --> 00:07:33.350
or maybe many of you here.

00:07:33.350 --> 00:07:35.150
If you're stuck in
an airplane seat--

00:07:35.150 --> 00:07:38.000
and some of you may have been
in an airplane quite recently--

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.240
you put on a headset and
something happens behind you.

00:07:41.240 --> 00:07:42.230
But you're strapped in.

00:07:42.230 --> 00:07:44.150
You can't get around.

00:07:44.150 --> 00:07:45.932
Well, what do you do?

00:07:45.932 --> 00:07:48.140
Well, one curb cut is
something that the Google Earth

00:07:48.140 --> 00:07:49.430
team solved.

00:07:49.430 --> 00:07:52.634
They actually rotate
the world around you.

00:07:52.634 --> 00:07:54.800
So you actually can have
what's happening behind you

00:07:54.800 --> 00:07:56.840
be moved into the front.

00:07:56.840 --> 00:08:00.350
Also, YouTube VR has solved
the same kind of problem

00:08:00.350 --> 00:08:02.490
by rotating the
world around you.

00:08:02.490 --> 00:08:05.090
So this way, you've improved
the world for people

00:08:05.090 --> 00:08:08.130
in wheelchairs, airplane
seats, or even your comfy bed.

00:08:11.780 --> 00:08:15.110
There are few standards today
in terms of accessibility

00:08:15.110 --> 00:08:16.820
around AR and VR.

00:08:16.820 --> 00:08:18.660
In fact, they are none.

00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:21.350
So here's an opportunity to
really do something exciting

00:08:21.350 --> 00:08:25.480
that could really
impact people's lives.

00:08:25.480 --> 00:08:29.470
Even before AR, people
were using devices

00:08:29.470 --> 00:08:31.730
to help improve their lives.

00:08:31.730 --> 00:08:34.240
People were using their
cameras on their cell phones

00:08:34.240 --> 00:08:35.910
to magnify something.

00:08:35.910 --> 00:08:37.659
Well, this is actually
an assistive device

00:08:37.659 --> 00:08:39.225
called a magnifier.

00:08:39.225 --> 00:08:41.600
But people didn't realize they
were using assistive tech.

00:08:41.600 --> 00:08:44.200
They were just using their
phone to magnify something.

00:08:44.200 --> 00:08:46.030
And it makes their life better.

00:08:46.030 --> 00:08:48.250
That's the whole idea.

00:08:48.250 --> 00:08:51.460
But now, with modern
AR and VR, you

00:08:51.460 --> 00:08:52.960
can fly anywhere in the world.

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:57.490
So someone who was stuck in
bed can visit the International

00:08:57.490 --> 00:08:59.050
Space Station.

00:08:59.050 --> 00:09:02.182
Or you can measure the
couch in your room.

00:09:02.182 --> 00:09:03.640
Or if the game is
designed as such,

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:05.290
you can sort of
see when someone's

00:09:05.290 --> 00:09:07.290
shooting from behind you.

00:09:07.290 --> 00:09:08.819
Or how about when
you're stressed?

00:09:08.819 --> 00:09:10.360
You can have the
most important piece

00:09:10.360 --> 00:09:13.330
of information highlighted
or have everything else

00:09:13.330 --> 00:09:15.100
be ignored for you.

00:09:15.100 --> 00:09:16.960
This is pretty
useful for everybody.

00:09:16.960 --> 00:09:19.480
And fortunately,
each of these things

00:09:19.480 --> 00:09:22.030
are also profoundly impactful
for people with different kinds

00:09:22.030 --> 00:09:24.010
of disabilities.

00:09:24.010 --> 00:09:25.840
And there's a lot of
ways that AR and VR

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:28.550
can help people, perhaps
in ways you don't expect.

